								<img src="i/dominant/block.gif" border="0" height="4" width="1"><br>
								Seeing as several of you are talking about this kind of thing in SWG, I thought some of you may want to read this.  It originally came from an SWG board.  Who knows, if Tz goes Empire it may be he will be considered a force for good, kinda different for Tz <img src="i/expressions/face-icon-small-smile.gif" border="0">  Oh, and as the original author pointed out .. we are talking about a game here and it would prolly be a good idea to refrain from any references to current events. It caused an incredible ruckus elsewhere.  It's a kinda long read.<BR><BR>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>This is a serious discussion. To many people, the Empire isn’t evil.<BR>Dev’s, be careful. When making content for the game, don’t make the Empire too evil. It has goals of peace and stability, and not just of conquest and enslavement.<BR><BR>Would you personally consider the Empire evil? It seriously depends on your point of view and perspective. Are you willing to sacrifice total freedom and self-determination in order for a guarantee of stability and peace? If so, you’d be an ardent supporter of the Empire. For many during the devastating Clone War and ensuing political fiasco, such a decision was a no brainier and too good to resist to end the terror and upheaval. Peace at all costs was the demands of many. Palpatine provided that peace happily.<BR><BR>This is an explanation of why the Empire is seen by many worlds and individuals as a protector of peace, and the Rebellion as a group of terrorists and traitors.<BR><BR>Military Power<BR>Imperial garrisons based on various worlds across the galaxy are “justified” and designed to maintain order and general peace, and prevent another full-scale war from ever breaking out. Any secessionist activity similar to that of the Clone War is rendered impossible by the massive Imperial army stationed all across the galaxy at important worlds and stations. Peace and the “establishment of justice” is secure by having a strong army of loyal Stormtroopers based on worlds, and not only stops trouble before it starts, but also drastically reduces crime and smuggling.<BR><BR>The Republic-era system of prideful and dangerous elite Jedi, who had to be called out and took a long time to reach distressed areas, is considered obsolete and dead to a great many people. The Imperial military prevents the huge growth of mega corporations that instigated the Clone War, such as the Trade Federation (likely gone), and forcibly prevents these guilds and corporations from maintaining huge armies. The Republic made similar moves after the Naboo Incident, but could not enforce them, rendering them meaningless and ineffective. The Empire carries out its laws and promises, something that the Republic miserably failed to do (With drastic consequences like the Clone War). This is seen as a vast improvement to many people.<BR><BR>Slavery<BR>Believe it or not, despite common belief, slavery is still outlawed during the Imperial Era. That’s directly from the developers of Star Wars Galaxies. The Empire does not openly enslave species in the public eye and flaunt it. It does so under the protective guise of “domestication” to species that are “prone to seditious and independent-minded actions”. It is also targeted only to certain species, which meet qualifications and are convenient to put to work. The general public is rather passive to Wookiee and other “slavery” by the Empire, because these species are prone to cause disturbances due to their mindsets (i.e. strong tendencies to democracy) which conflict with the Empire’s policies and form of government. Order must be maintained, so these species must be taken out of a position of which they can do harm to the general peace of the galaxy.<BR><BR>Although this is a huge generalization on the Empires part, the Empire puts out a lot of propaganda to prop up these beliefs. These species, regardless of individuals, are branded as a whole as “prone to treason” and must be “dealt with” or otherwise greater consequences will follow. The Empire’s propaganda, shown by the massive disbelief in the Force, is very effective. The general public overlooks Imperial “slavery”, and sees it in the interests of maintaining order.<BR><BR>The Emperor and his path to power<BR>The Emperor Palpatine is seen as a hero by a great number of people. He has massive popularity among the Core systems, and he is the inventor and embodiment of the peace and stability in the galaxy. His popularity is unrivaled to any Chancellor who served the Republic in several centuries, despite him being a rather reclusive figure. Busts and statues of him are displayed across the galaxy, and he has a massive one based on Coruscant, which shows him holding the Orb of Peace, a custom from his native world Naboo (Which has a pacifist reputation that bolsters Palpatine’s position). He has a position much to that of Hitler, although you realize that by the end of WW2, people were jubilant that Hitler was dead, much like people were so of Palatine after Endor. People realized the mistake they made in both cases.<BR><BR>Prepare for another canonical surprise. The Emperor Palpatine is only known to be a Sith Lord by very very very few people. Only the most elite of the elite know this secret and disturbing fact. Prince Xizor, the Emperors personal advisors (the guys we see following Palpatine around on the Death Star II), and Darth Vader are the only ones trusted with this dark secret as far as consistent canon and Lucas’s intentions are concerned. Even the highest Moffs and Admirals are excluded from this information. We know this from two basic things. If there was such disbelief in the Force, it is impossible for the public to know that the Emperor of the galactic government is a Sith Lord. You would think that all the Imperial admirals and officers, namely Admiral Motti confronting Vader, would have a much healthier respect for the Jedi and the Force if they knew that their Emperor was a Sith Lord trained in Jedi arts. Darth Vader however is known as a Jedi generally, and is considered the “last remnant of an ancient religion”. Both officers, and even common citizens know he is a Sith Lord, and call him by his title, “My Lord”. Even a common man in Shadows of the Empire collapsed in fear upon seeing Darth Vader, and called him, “My Lord”.<BR><BR>Even fewer, perhaps no one at all in the galaxy alive at this time, knows of Palaptine’s full story of his rise to power. No one knows of his role as Darth Sidious, save Darth Vader, and even his knowledge is sketchy. No one knows of all Palpatine’s hypocritical, sly, power-hungry plans and actions to tear down the Republic, like him approaching the Trade Federation to blockade Naboo, and then instigating the devastating Clone War where billions died as pawns of the Sith.<BR><BR>General Policies<BR>The Empire maintains order on the world of Sullust in a rather ironic way, by the same type of organization that instigated the Clone War, a mega corporation. Many people see this as living proof that the Empire as successfully “reined in” the corporations, and economic and industrial growth is now safe again, without the worry of corporations raising armies and staring wars. The Empire is also nationalizing a lot of industry and commerce in much of the Galactic Core, to create economic and political stability, and to keep the need for taxes very low. Taxes are hardly the same yoke as they were from the Republic-era. It is a huge improvement from the burdens and insane payments of the Republic-era taxpayer. Many people love this, and thus support the Empire<BR><BR>Insurrections that cause bloodshed are crushed immediately without delay, a strong improvement to many people. Darth Vader and his personnel immediately overwhelmed the planet of Zalorris when it tried to break away from the Empire. The Republic would have debated the issue to death, and eventually given a reprimand and diplomatic protest. Peace and order are to be maintained at all costs.<BR><BR>Alderaan and Propaganda.<BR>A psychopathic and despotic commander in charge of Death Star, Grand Moff Tarkin, carried out the Alderaan incident. This is one of the true underside evils of the Empire. However, the Empire is never evil in public, never flaunts evil, and tries to keep up a good face of being the galactic guardian. Propaganda solved this. Just like the propaganda pumped out by Germany, which talked of “invading Polish armies” and “Polish troop masses on borders”, the Empire distorted the real situation, and even outright lied. And guess what, the vast German public believed the lies that they were spoon-fed. Although the below is technically not canon, it fits with Lucas’s intentions and vision, displaying the Empire’s lies to keep up the charade that it’s the guardian of peace. It is from my bio, as my character received information from Imperial controlled news networks on Coruscant.<BR><BR>Coruscanti Globe<BR><BR>“It is most regrettable that the world of Alderaan was destroyed after committing an act of war. I did all I could to protect the families and loyal servants of the Empire on board the Death Star. The system of Alderaan was planning to lead a revolt against the Emperor, and had just started a state of rearmament. We had to stop them before they could cause more bloodshed. Princess Leia Organa of Alderaan even admitted herself to be planning for a war against our peaceful Empire”. – Grand Moff Tarkin<BR><BR>“I was personally hurt by our choice to strike against the Alderaan rebellion. I do go about life at much more ease however, knowing that the women and children of our Empire can sleep safely, without the threat of another full-scale war.” – General Tagge<BR><BR>“We all wanted to avoid it. It just couldn’t happen though. Guerillas of the Rebel Alliance even opened fire on a diplomatic team we sent down to the surface to try to end the situation peacefully and bring Alderaan back into the Empire. I was deeply saddened by our recourse to open fire on Alderaan and destroy the infection.” – Admiral Motti<BR><BR>Dev’s, please don’t make the Empire super-evil and abusive in public. Make its outward goals and positions clear. It wants peace and stability.<BR><BR>It wants order, not war or enslavement. Don’t make every single NCP who refers to the Empire say something about it being evil. Make the general public rather passive and even some sympathetic to the government.<BR><BR><BR>  
								</font>
				           
														
							</td>
